Zeno of Elea, a celebrated philosopher, pupil of Parmenides, flourished about 460 B.C. The story of his firmness under tortures inflieted upon him by a tyrant. against whom he had conspired is referred to by numerous authorities—Diog. L. lx 6, 263 Plut. de Rep. Stoic. 37, 3, p. ¹0513 adu. Colot. 32, 10, p. 1126; Philostr. Life of Apoll. vii 25 Clem. Alex. Strom. iv 486 e; Tertull. Apol. c. 50; Nemesius de Nat. Hom. c. 30, p. 233 ed. Oxon.; Suidas s.v. Ἐλὲα; val. Max. iii 3, 2-53 see Davies⁷ n. here and Zeller, Fre—Soc. Sclzool5‚ 1 pp. 609- 103 but the accounts vary greatly in all details, eg. as to the place of the oecur- rence, the name of the tyrant, etc.
